  "model": "claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
  "response_text": "# 3-Day Heart-Healthy Nigerian Meal Plan\n\n## Day 1\n\n**Breakfast:** Oatmeal with banana and groundnuts\n- Steel-cut oats with cinnamon, sliced banana, crushed unsalted groundnuts, and a drizzle of honey\n\n**Lunch:** Vegetable soup with lean fish\n- Tomato-based vegetable soup (carrots, spinach, celery, tomatoes) with grilled catfish\n- Served with brown rice or boiled yam\n\n**Dinner:** Baked tilapia with steamed vegetables\n- Herb-seasoned baked tilapia (lemon, garlic, ginger)\n- Steamed broccoli and sweet potato\n\n---\n\n## Day 2\n\n**Breakfast:** Akamu (cornmeal) with okra soup\n- Smooth cornmeal porridge with light okra soup (minimal palm oil, lean meat)\n\n**Lunch:** Jollof rice with grilled chicken\n- Brown rice jollof with tomatoes, onions, and minimal oil\n- Skinless grilled chicken breast\n\n**Dinner:** Moi moi with salad\n- Steamed bean pudding (use egg whites, reduce oil)\n- Fresh garden salad with lemon dressing\n\n---\n\n## Day 3\n\n**Breakfast:** Scrambled eggs with whole wheat bread\n- 2 eggs (mostly whites) with whole grain bread and sliced tomatoes\n\n**Lunch:** Egusi soup with fish\n- Melon seed soup with spinach and grilled catfish\n- Served with cassava fufu or boiled plantain\n\n**Dinner:** Pepper soup with vegetables\n- Spiced fish pepper soup with carrots, celery, and ginger\n- Side of brown rice\n\n---\n\n## Heart-Healthy Tips for Nigerian Cooking\n- **Reduce palm oil** or use in minimal amounts\n- **Grill or bake** instead of deep-frying\n- **Use lean proteins**: fish, skinless chicken, legumes\n- **Increase vegetables** in soups and stews\n- **Limit processed seasonings**; use fresh herbs and spices\n- **Choose whole grains** over white rice/refined carbs",
